PART 4 — REFACTORED CELLS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Apply these principles INSIDE the single notebook:

▸ Python idioms (Quick Python Book Ch 5–15)
  - pathlib.Path for all paths
  - f-strings; explicit encoding="utf-8"
  - `with open(...)` everywhere
  - dataclasses for records and config
  - @property for computed attributes
  - Narrow except + custom exceptions; raise ... from e
  - Generators for big sequences
  - enumerate / zip / comprehensions
  - Type hints on every function
  - Google-style docstrings

▸ Design principles (Mastering Python Design Patterns)
  - SOLID — especially SRP per function/class
  - DRY, KISS, YAGNI
  - Composition over inheritance
  - Dependency Injection (pass deps as args, no globals)

▸ Patterns to use IN-NOTEBOOK where they reduce complexity:
  - Factory  → model/loader selection from config
  - Strategy → swap algorithms (scaler, splitter)
  - Facade   → the Pipeline class in Cell 13
  - Chain of Responsibility → preprocessing steps
  - Repository → data access in Cell 7
  - Decorator → @log_step, @checkpoint, @timeit on functions

▸ Restart strategy (replaces what we lose vs multi-file):
  - Every stage writes its output to ./checkpoints/<stage>.<ext>
  - Pipeline checks for checkpoint before running stage
  - Force-recompute flag in config to override
  - Log start/end of every stage with duration

▸ Logging (replaces what we lose vs proper project):
  - logger = logging.getLogger("pipeline")
  - logs/run_YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS.log via FileHandler
  - INFO for stage transitions, DEBUG for details, ERROR for failures
  - Decorator @log_step wraps every public function

